⁴* Dr. Verrall, in his ‘studies in Horace,' has an ingenious chapter in which he argues that the Lamia of this Epistle and the two Odes is none other than the ‘vilicus' himself, the name being here substituted for the personal pronoun, as ‘Horatius’ for ‘ego’ in the pre- ceding line. It follows that ‘ moratur' and ¹ istuc fert ¹ must mean ‘ hinders me from’ and ‘drives me to' the discussion to follow. This is in itself an objection to the view. The words are singularly unlike Horace’s usual ironical way of entering upon a philosophical lecture. There is also the same difficulty which weighs against the reading ‘Pulliae' in Od. 3. 4. 10, the un- likelihood of such a personal detail in the poet's life having escaped notice in early times. It also makes the ‘vilicus' a much more important person in the Epistle than on our theory he is.
